# End-to-End Workflow

The interviews suggest the following operational workflow:

## 1. Screening and Identification

Individuals must first be screened for HIV, SUD, and related service needs.

Risks at this stage include:

- inconsistent intake procedures
- staffing limitations
- insufficient screening capacity
- resource constraints

---

## 2. In-Jail Service Coordination

After identification, multiple care systems must coordinate services within the correctional environment.

This includes:

- HIV treatment
- medication for opioid use disorder (MOUD)
- mental health support
- case management
- referral coordination

A recurring issue is weak service coordination between providers and operational teams. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

---

## 3. Staff Adoption and Workflow Execution

The implementation process depends heavily on whether staff consistently adopt evidence-based practices.

The interviews identify several operational blockers:

- provider stigma
- inconsistent protocol adherence
- insufficient training
- workflow resistance
- difficulty adopting new technologies

This creates onboarding and adoption risk across implementation sites.

---

## 4. Community Transition and Follow-Up

Continuity of care after release is one of the most fragile workflow stages.

Key risks include:

- transportation barriers
- weak coordination with community providers
- inconsistent patient follow-up
- limited resource availability

Even if in-jail implementation succeeds, breakdowns during transition may significantly reduce long-term effectiveness. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

